text.text:
One thing you might not know about us is that we're big advocates of the lesser-spotted late night cafe. The places that, come 6pm, shift into something laid-back and moody, where we strongly suspect we'd be capable of seducing anyone in the entire world. 

Here you'll find us leisurely holding an after-hours espresso, sipping on a lil' negroni, maybe even indulging in a small bite, all without the noise of a pub or the formalities of a restaurant. Join us.

tip.text:
Isreali-inspired Bernstein’s Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it’s another vibey spot to add to Clapton’s growing arsenal.

text.text: Clapton has its very own slice of Tel Aviv cool at a corner favourite that pairs levantine small plates with all the necessary libations. Ideal for taking a seat outside, and watching the Clapton cool cats bop on by.

tip.text: An iconic Soho institution, this is as close to feeling the rhythms of an Italian cafe at 3am as you're going to get. You can grab pizza, coffee or sandwiches at pretty much any time of day - expect to encounter London's gregarious Italian community whilst you're at it. It's a prime, lively spot for early morning munchies and late night drinking.

text.text: An iconic Soho institution, this is as close to feeling the rhythms of an Italian cafe at 3am as you're going to get. You can grab pizza, coffee or sandwiches at any time of day - expect to encounter London's gregarious Italian community whilst you're at it.

tip.text:
Amid the bookies, 24 hour gyms and chicken shops on Walworth Road, Louie Louie stands out as a rare charismatic gem on that familiar chic-cafe-morphs-into-vibey-restaurant-and-cocktail-den tip. Good coffee, good brunch, and good bakes dominate the day, but really you wanna head here when the sun disappears and evening descends.

That’s when a revolving kitchen residency provides the small plates, a vintage hi-spec sound system provides the crisp jams and skilled bartenders get to work on original, tongue-teasing cocktails. Heading downstairs to the dark drinking den with a couple of cocktails in hand and that soulful music in your ears should provide all the fuel you need for those intimate convos we know you like so damn much.

text.text: When evening turns up, this bougie Elly & Castle cafe/restaurant transforms into a setting ideal for a Deep Meaningful Conversation. Delicious small plates are paired with intriguing cocktails and soundtracked by a very nifty speaker system, dealing in easy-listening soul and funk.

tip.text:
It might take a little while to find amidst Tottenham’s warehouse district, but once you reach Craving Coffee you'll discover all you need for a relaxing sip, bite or chill. The light pours in from their south-facing windows, illuminating soft woods, white tiles and, most importantly, delicious coffee and healthy bites from a kitchen where food is not just an afterthought.

Coffee was their starting point, but now they’re up to all sorts - lunch and dinner here feature carefully constructed European dishes with high quality ingredients. The food has certainly gone to their head with supper clubs sitting alongside a bill of exhibitions and other cultural happenings from the Tottenham community. Yes sir, it's a local favourite.

text.text:
From their humble coffee origins, Craving Coffee has quickly become a Tottenham hotspot - particularly a little later in the day when their all-week alcohol licence comes in handy. 
Amongst the soft woods, white tiles and chic-warehouse aesthetic, expect ideal conditions to get a little loose and plenty full.

tip.text:
Having shaken off its old greasy spoon shell and fluffed up its feathers with a swish new coffee machine and drinks counter, the Cable Bar & Cafe has now been reborn as a trendy phoenix that oozes laid-back suave. Tucked a hop, skip and a jump away from Oval station, it’s a spot that tickles all your fancies, whether those involve kicking back with a book on your ones; flexing your creative muscles with the help of their super fast WiFi; or chin wagging with friends over some cocktails.

Snag yourself a window seat for prime people watching or slither into one of their cubby holes inside where the decor is a treasure trove of mismatch furniture, bovine prints and a single banjo hung proudly above the bar. Every Tuesday there’s live jazz and, as expected, the quaint, pine space gets absolutely jam-packed with thirsty groove seekers.

text.text: One of Kennington's best haunts, Cable is all dark woods, mismatched furniture and fast internet. It's very chill during the day, and marginally less chill come nightfall when most of the trendy sorts in these parts stop by for a bev. Watch out for their excellent jazz nights on Tuesdays.

tip.text:
Run by the super friendly Diddy herself, this is an all-day cafe/bar that's quickly become a local hub - the kind of place where you'll overhear a convo going on next to you and feel compelled to join in. They're not trying to do anything too fancy here, just provide a colourful, chilled spot to unwind, chat and feel at home, and we're big fans.

A short menu offers staple brunch bits, and if you’re after something stronger, there’s a reasonably priced cocktail list to check too (£5.50 Aperol spritzes... for real). London is short on continental-style places to get cocktails late without the formalities of a bar; this is just that laid-back ticket.

text.text: The community vibes run strong at Diddy's: a colourful Mare Street all-day cafe where locals bundle in to cotch amongst the low lights. It's a refreshingly simple affair, with cocktails all around the £6-7 mark and reliably good jams. There's also a downstairs den for something a little more intimate.

tip.text:
Tucked away in East Dulwich, Rock Steady Rum Lounge (formerly Blue Mountain Cafe) has fast become a communal, neighbourhood cafe and restaurant with a real friendly and cosy vibe: perfect for either a coffee in daylight or a glass of something strong. The decor is arty and unique, with plenty of nods to its Jamaican owners' heritage - and plenty of Bob playing on the speakers.

The breakfast and brunch menu features the usual suspects (look out for the organic Full Monty), though is a little pricey, whilst their sourdough sandwiches and soups are also pretty popular. In the evening, there's a real Caribbean feel with dishes like curried goat; saltfish; and jerk chicken - all decent, though lacking a bit of spice. As night falls, get set for cocktails and some of that rocksteady music.

text.text: Injecting East Dulwich with its laid-back Caribbean charm since '93, Blue Mountain Cafe is an arty, bohemian kind of spot that deals in rum-orientated drinks, jerk chicken and all round positivity. If none of that sounds good, perhaps there's no hope for you.

tip.text:
Cafes are a dime a dozen in this work-crazy patch of town, but Catalyst is a little different. On a quieter road adjacent to the nutty Leather Lane, this minimalist, light space is an altogether calmer, more chilled affair; suitable for catching up with a pal over some of their in-house roasted coffee or chewing over something spicy and filling from a short lunch menu that packs some intriguing lil punches.

Nope this place is not about limp sandwiches and the like. Instead, scope out the avo baba ganoush on sourdough, with marinated peppers and tahini sauce - it's got a real nice heat to it - or the halloumi katsu & fried egg sandwich. Whether you're on the solo remote working tip or the languid lunch tip, Catalyst is a trusty spot that never seems to get too busy.

text.text: Cafes are two a penny round these workaholic Clerkenwell ends; cafes that stay open late (at least on Thursday and Friday) are not. Catalyst is a calming spot serving craft beers, wines and cocktails till 10 - a great shout for a post-work sip somewhere quiet.

tip.text:
An Exmouth Market institution, Brill Café is the kind of homely, charming and assuredly indie café we’d write a song about were we in the songwriting business. Run by Jeremy Brill, who famously cycles to Brick Lane to get their bagels every morning, this place revolves around a particular holy trinity: music, bagels and coffee - which all, in their own way, bring a pure dose of pleasure.

The bagels are lightly toasted marvels, packed full of salmon, ham or cheese; their own-brew Coffee Officina blend tastes terrifically creamy with milk; and you can expect soulful, jazzy numbers all day long on vinyl which can also be bought along with a host of CDs. What makes this place stand out, though, is the sense of heartfelt bohemian community - plus a magical sun-trap garden that most of Exmouth doesn’t know about.

text.text: Come Friday evenings in summer, there are plenty worse places to be than Brill on Exmouth Market which opens up its magical little secret garden for booze beneath the fairy lights. Add in an exceptional soundtrack courtesy of Brill's record collection and you're onto something pretty darn pleasant.

tip.text:
Waterloo has many a dodgy trap, but this place is a much-needed gem: a cafe and bar where rickety furniture and bits of old Vespas sit alongside vintage espresso machines and roaming cats. It’s got an old-school Italian character to it that is a welcome change of pace - where, if you’re lucky enough to grab a seat, you might end up in convos about art, politics and the general intricacies of life.

By day, it’s a cafe doing really nice coffee, tasty home-made cakes and with the rare treat of being able to bring your own food in from the nearby market (if you ask nicely). By night, things step up a couple of notches with one of their Italian beers going down nicely.

text.text: Waterloo has many a dodgy trap, but this place is a real gem: a cafe and bar where rickety furniture and bits of old Vespas sit alongside vintage espresso machines. By night, things step up a couple of notches, with one of their Italian beers going down nicely.

tip.text:
We're big into theatre cafes because, aside from when things begin to swing at showtime, they're tranquil, comfy places, ripe for an afternoon cotch. Park Theatre is in that mould: a softly lit, lazy place where cultured locals come to chew the fat, pinch some free wifi and just generally let the day roll on by, aided by the gentle hubbub of life itself.

The menu actually covers a fair amount including breakfast options, sandwiches and stone-baked pizzas coming in at around a tenner. Union coffee and the usual cocktail suspects complete the fuelling.

text.text: A softly lit, lazy place where cultured locals come to chew the fat, pinch some free wifi and just generally let the day roll on by. They've a decent selection of wines and beers, whilst cocktails are at the £8 mark.

tip.text:
Half cafe, half bike workshop, it's no surprise that this place is legendary with two-wheelin' folk in London. There's Square Mile coffee constantly on the go here, homemade pies, cakes, a decent beer selection, and free WiFi (plenty of power sockets around too which is almost more important).

Any problem you're having with your pride and joy, they'll be able to help you out in the workshop. Even if you can't ride a bike without using stabilisers, this is a great place to hang out.

text.text: An Old Street staple, drop by here in the evening and you'll find Square Mile coffee, as much wifi as you can handle, draft beer and a menu of burgers, toasties and salads. And bikes, of course, so please do come wearing lycra.

tip.text:
The question on everyone's (our) lips is: how does Notes manage to be such a quality little coffee haven when it's right beside Trafalgar Square? Yeah, it gets busy, but never rammed, and there's a distinct lack of teenage Italian tourist swarms.

The coffee is definitely on point, but the doughnuts are the star here. Seriously, get one. The big table under the skylight is prime real estate to veg out at, and order a glass of wine here (they've got a good selection). Notes, don't go changin' now.

text.text: Amongst the excitable tourist swarms of Trafalgar Square, Notes is a welcome respite: an all-day cafe and wine bar open late, bringing small sharing plates, charcuterie boards and £10 cocktails to the evening party.

tip.text:
Homerton seems to have had a makeover recently and Hatch has definitely had a part to play in it. Converted from a warehouse into a multi purpose space, Hatch's spacious and thoughtfully designed space houses an all-day cafe, juice bar and plenty of hot desks - perfect place to get those creative juices flowing. Check the website to get informed on all the tasty art workshops, talks, film nights and events from local creatives.

Food-wise they've pretty much got everything that might tickle your fancy. Vanilla and cinnamon waffle? Yup. Bean and roasted red pepper quesadilla? Tick. Mediterranean grilled halloumi flatbread with beetroot and tzatziki? Oh you betta believe it, sugar. They've also got a fab selection of booze, and a bangin' Happy Hour 5-7pm.

text.text: Homerton's Hatch tries to be all things to all men: a cafe/workspace/event space/bar/hip hangout in a converted warehouse where all kinds of things happen in the evening. But if nothing's organised, this is a suitably chilled spot for a coffee, beer or glass of wine potentially paired with one of their hearty dishes.

tip.text:
Blink whilst walking past this itty-bitty café and you might just miss it; clutching onto the front of a fully functioning upholstery workshop, Fowlds has been breathing life into the old ‘good things, small packages’ thing since 2014. By day you’re looking at all kinds of homemade pastries, cake and coffee, whilst the evening brings with it bar snacks, craft beer and zingy cocktails.

There may be somewhat of a table shortage inside but ample seating tumbles out onto the road, providing a great spot to park up and gaze at the original 1926 upholsterers’ signage hanging out front. If you’re lucky, you might even catch craft upholstery in action. Furniture restoration and coffee? Name a more iconic duo, we’ll wait.

text.text: Another one strictly for Fridays in summer, the community-owned Fowlds is a very cute spot in the front space of a fully functioning upholstery workshop. It's that iconic duo: furniture restoration and coffee, only with a couple of added extras we know you need to feel happy: snacks, craft beers, wine, cocktails and a selection of whiskies.
